eta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92479"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a two-month history of increasing fatigue, muscle weakness and weight gain. She has not been sleeping well and has been feeling down during this time. On examination, her blood pressure is 150/94 mmHg, pulse 84/min and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her body mass index is 36 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. She has bruises on her arms and red cheeks. Laboratory findings show a mild hypernatraemia and mild hypokalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brain MRI","Morning serum cortisol level","Corticotropin-releasing hormone test","Overnight dexamethasone suppression test","Random salivary cortisol level"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECushing\u0027s disease is a rare condition and the variety of clinical symptoms and signs that may exist, together with a scatter of biochemical findings, can make the diagnosis challenging. However, the clinical picture and electrolytes changes described in this scenario make the diagnosis reasonably apparent. Some 70 % of Cushing\u0027s disease cases originate from an adrenocorticotrophin-secreting pituitary adenoma, leading to increased cortisol secretion from the adrenal glands.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EMultiple screening tests can be used for patients suspected of cortisol excess:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMidnight salivary or serum cortisol\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E24-hour urinary free cortisol\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOvernight dexamethasone suppression test\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach of these tests has benefits and caveats; the clinician should judge the most suitable test balancing patient factors and local availability. For patients with a high index of suspicion, as in this case, repeated individual tests and multiple different tests should be considered for cross-confirmation. In such cases, early referral to an endocrinologist is recommended for specialist interpretation of results, which can be complex and confounded by multiple factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf the available options, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eovernight dexamethasone suppression test\u003C/strong\u003E is the appropriate choice. It has high acceptability in outpatient settings, and involves the patient taking a 1 mg dose of dexamethasone between 11 pm and midnight, then attending for a serum cortisol sample at 8-9 am the following morning. A cortisol level of \u0026lt;50 nmol/L is the normal physiological response with a functioning HPA axis, and has high sensitivity (95%) and moderate specificity (80%) for excluding Cushing\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom untimed cortisol tests\u003C/strong\u003E, whether in serum or \u003Cstrong\u003Esaliva\u003C/strong\u003E, have limited value in assessing cortisol disorders due to significant fluctuations during the day. However, late evening samples (11 pm-midnight) are used for screening for excess, while early \u003Cstrong\u003Emorning samples\u003C/strong\u003E (8-9 am) are used for screening assessing deficiency, taking advantage of broad circadian patterns of peak and trough. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrain MRI\u003C/strong\u003E and a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorticotropin-releasing hormone test \u003C/strong\u003Emay be indicated but only once hypercortisolism has been confirmed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The low-dose dexamethasone suppression test is a reliable investigation for Cushing\u0027s disease.","Random blood or saliva cortisol levels have limited use in diagnosing Cushing\u0027s disease."],"references":["Hanna FWF, Issa BG, Kevil B, Fryer AA. Investigating cortisol excess or deficiency: a practical approach. BMJ. 2019;367:l6039. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31771937/","Pappachan et al. Cushing\u0027s syndrome: a practical approach to diagnosis and differential diagnoses. J Clin Pathol. 2017;70(4):350-359. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28069628/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75776"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"92"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75776"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T21:16:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T21:28:54+10:30","number":8,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-03-17T21:28:12+10:30","plagiarismScore":8.1,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-92-8.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250928T141832Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=3b9aadea7a9d6de127542303b28396d4c4a1f014c6ff3733ff57f6fa91e74264"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"92"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92479"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"2888"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{